definition.value: A member of the class of benzyl alcohols in which the hydrogen at position 4 on the phenyl ring of benzyl alcohol has been replaced by an isopropyl group.
The intermediate in the biosynthesis of vitamin B12 from uroporphyrinogen III in which five methyl groups have been introduced into the tetrapyrrole framework, together with ring contraction.
An N-acylglycine resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of (5-hydroxyindol-3-yl)acetic acid with the amino group of glycine.
A methyl ketone that is acetone in which one of the methyl groups has been replaced by a phenyl group.
A dichlorohydroquinone that is hydroquinone substituted by chloro groups at positions 2 and 6.
The epoxy steroid formed from cholest-5-ene by formal addition of oxygen across the 5,6 double bond with alpha-configuration at both C-5 and C-6.
A catechol that is the 3,4-dihydroxy derivative of mandelic acid; a metabolite of L-dopa.
A cobalt group element atom that has atomic number 27.
An acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of (E)-2-benzylidenesuccinic acid.

A dicarboximide that is 4-(2-hydroxyethyl)piperidine-2,6-dione in which one of the hydrogens attached to the carbon  bearing the hydroxy group is replaced by a 3,5-dimethyl-2-oxocyclohexyl group. It is an antibiotic produced by the bacterium Streptomyces griseus.
An ether having methyl and tert-butyl as the two alkyl components.
A member of the class of tetracyclines with formula C22H23ClN2O8 isolated from Streptomyces aureofaciens.
A dTDP-sugar having 3-dehydro-4,6-dideoxy-alpha-D-glucose as the sugar component.
An oxo-fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxylic acid group of 3-oxohexanoic acid.
A glucotriose consisting of two alpha-D-glucopyranose residues and a D-glucopyranose residue joined in sequence by (1->6) glycosidic bonds.
A 2',3'-cyclic pyrimidine nucleotide in which cytidine is the parent nucleoside.
A member of the class of dihydrochalcones that is dihydrochalcone substituted by hydroxy groups at positions 4, 2', and 4' respectively.

A pyranoindolizinoquinoline that is pyrano[3',4':6,7]indolizino[1,2-b]quinoline which is substituted by oxo groups at positions 3 and 14, and by an ethyl group and a hydroxy group at position 4 (the S enantiomer).
A dicarboxylic acid monoamide obtained by the formal condensation of amino group of L-glutamic 5-semialdehyde with one of the carboxy groups of succinic acid.
Any aldehyde having an oxo substituent at the 2-position.

A tetracyclic diterpenoid that has an tetradecahydro-8,11a-methanocyclohepta[a]naphthalene skeleton with two hydroxymethyl substituents at positions 4 and 9, two methyl substituents at positions 4 and 11b and two hydroxy substituents at positions 3 and 9. An antibiotic with antiviral and antimitotical properties. Aphidicolin is a reversible inhibitor of eukaryotic nuclear DNA replication.
A cardenolide glycoside that consists of strophanthidin having a 6-deoxy-alpha-L-mannopyranosyl (L-rhamnosyl) group attached at position 3.
A 3-oxoacyl-CoA having its S-acyl component derived from 2-oxocyclohexane-1-carboxylic acid.
A D-galactopyranose having beta configuration at the anomeric centre.
A hydroxy fatty acyl-CoA that results from the formal condensation of the thiol group of coenzyme A with the carboxy group of (S)-3-hydroxydodecanoic acid.
A flavanone glycoside that is (-)-taxifolin substituted by a alpha-L-rhamnosyl moiety at position 3 via a glycosidic linkage.
A pentahydroxyflavone that is kaempferol substituted by a hydroxy group at position 8. It is a natural flavonoid from flaxseed which exerts antioxidant, anti-inflammatory and anticancer activities.
